      <hedline>
        <hl1>Legal Shoes</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Sander Vanocur letter comments on the reference to a 'white shoe' law firm in a June 17 article</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In your article about Kathleen Cleaver (''Memories of a Proper Girl Who Was a Panther,'' Arts &amp; Ideas pages, June 17), she is said to have gone to ''work with the white-shoe Manhattan firm of Cravath, Swaine &amp; Moore.''</p>
        <p>What is a ''white shoe'' law firm? Is it different from a ''brown shoe'' law firm?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In your article about Kathleen Cleaver (''Memories of a Proper Girl Who Was a Panther,'' Arts &amp; Ideas pages, June 17), she is said to have gone to ''work with the white-shoe Manhattan firm of Cravath, Swaine &amp; Moore.''</p>
        <p>What is a ''white shoe'' law firm? Is it different from a ''brown shoe'' law firm?</p>
        <p>If a lawyer from Cravath, Swaine &amp; Moore asked to approach the bench and did so while wearing a dark suit and white shoes, would not the judge be inclined to hold that lawyer in contempt of court?</p>
        <p>SANDER VANOCUR  Santa Barbara, Calif.  June 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
